====Etymology====
Old English ''[[standan]]'' < Proto-Germanic '''*standan''' < Proto-Indo-European '''*sth<sub>2</sub><u>n</u>d<font size=-2>H</font>-''' < '''[[Wiktionary Appendix:Proto-Indo-European roots|*steh<sub>2</sub>-]]'''

===Verb===
[[Category:English irregular verbs]]
{{en-verb2|'''to stand'''|'''[[stands]]'''|'''[[stood]]'''|'''[[stood]]'''|'''[[standing]]'''}}

#{{intransitive}} To be upright, support oneself on the feet in an erect position.
#:''Here I stand, wondering what to do next.''
#{{intransitive}} To rise to one's feet; to [[stand up]].
#:''Stand up, walk to the refrigerator, and get your own snack.''
#{{intransitive}} To remain motionless.
#:''Do not leave your car standing in the road.''
#{{intransitive}} {{cricket}} To act as an [[umpire]].
#{{intransitive}} To [[undergo]]; [[withstand]]; [[hold up]].
#:''The works of Shakespeare have stood the test of time.''
#{{intransitive}} To [[tolerate]].
#:''I can't stand when people don't read the instructions.''
#{{intransitive}} To place in an upright or standing position.
#:''He stood the broom in a corner and took a break.''
#{{transitive}} To [[tolerate]].
#:''I can't '''stand''' her.''

